{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644342"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:04:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:04:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18043"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18043"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10757"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73360"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10757"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18043"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58831"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"10208"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25094"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25098"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73360"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about intramembranous ossification is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["It involves a cartilage template.","It does not involve the formation of an ossification centre.","Woven bone is initially formed and later replaced by lamellar bone.","It primarily occurs in long bones.","Osteoid is laid down in an organised manner."],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWoven bone is initially formed and later replaced by lamellar bone\u003C/strong\u003E during intramembranous ossification. This process involves the direct formation of bone without a cartilage template, which is characteristic of endochondral ossification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt involves a cartilage template\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because intramembranous ossification does not use a cartilage model; this is a feature of endochondral ossification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoid is laid down in an organised manner\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because, during the initial stages of intramembranous ossification, osteoid is laid down in a disorganised manner, forming woven bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt primarily occurs in long bones\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because intramembranous ossification primarily occurs in flat bones, such as those of the skull and clavicle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt does not involve the formation of an ossification centre\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because both intramembranous and endochondral ossification involve the formation of an ossification centre where bone formation begins.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intramembranous ossification involves the direct formation of bone without a cartilage template.","Woven bone is initially formed during intramembranous ossification and is later replaced by lamellar bone.","Osteoid is laid down in a disorganised manner during the initial stages of intramembranous ossification."],"references":["Gartner, L. P. (2020). Textbook of histology e-book: Textbook of histology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Baig MA, Bacha D. Histology, Bone. 2023 May 1. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31082176","Blumer MJF. Bone tissue and histological and molecular events during development of the long bones. Ann Anat. 2021 May;235:151704. doi: 10.1016/j.aanat.2021.151704. Epub 2021 Feb 16. PMID: 33600952","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746. doi: 10.1155/2015/421746. Epub 2015 Jul 13. PMID: 26247020; PMCID: PMC4515490"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58831"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18043"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58831"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T11:54:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T11:55:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10757"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73360"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"i